  "text": "The Android Activity lifecycle is implemented across four key files in the AOSP platform_frameworks_base repository:\n\n1. **Activity.java** (core/java/android/app/Activity.java): The base Activity class that extends ContextThemeWrapper. This is the public-facing class that applications subclass to create Activities. It contains the lifecycle methods onCreate(), onStart(), onResume(), onPause(), onStop(), and onDestroy().\n\n2. **ActivityThread.java** (core/java/android/app/ActivityThread.java): The main thread handler for Android applications, extending ClientTransactionHandler. ActivityThread is the runtime responsible for executing lifecycle transitions triggered from the system server. It processes ClientTransaction objects that contain lifecycle state changes.\n\n3. **ActivityRecord.java** (services/core/java/com/android/server/wm/ActivityRecord.java): The server-side representation of an Activity within the WindowManager service. ActivityRecord maintains the state of running activities on the server side and is responsible for managing the activity's window, visibility, and transitions.\n\n4. **ActivityTaskManagerService.java** (services/core/java/com/android/server/wm/ActivityTaskManagerService.java): The system service that manages activity stacks, tasks, and the overall activity state. ActivityTaskManagerService coordinates activity launches, transitions, and manages the stack hierarchy. It makes decisions about which activities to launch and when lifecycle transitions should occur.\n\nThese four files form the core of the Activity lifecycle implementation, with the client-side Activity and ActivityThread handling execution, and the server-side ActivityRecord and ActivityTaskManagerService managing orchestration and state."
}
EOF

